00:44:32.610 --> 00:44:34.590 align:middle line:84%
I put one stem cell
in culture by itself.

00:44:34.590 --> 00:44:36.320 align:middle line:90%
It divides every 10 or 12 hours.

00:44:36.320 --> 00:44:40.510 align:middle line:84%
At first, there's one, then
2, 4, 8, 16, 32, doubling.

00:44:40.510 --> 00:44:42.750 align:middle line:84%
So I have 50,000
genetically identical cells.

00:44:42.750 --> 00:44:43.900 align:middle line:90%
That's not the experiment.

00:44:43.900 --> 00:44:44.820 align:middle line:90%
This is.

00:44:44.820 --> 00:44:48.030 align:middle line:84%
I split the cells into three
different Petri dishes.

00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:51.540 align:middle line:84%
And what I do is I change
the chemical composition

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:53.370 align:middle line:90%
of the culture medium.

00:44:53.370 --> 00:44:56.740 align:middle line:84%
Culture medium is the
equivalent of blood.

00:44:56.740 --> 00:44:59.247 align:middle line:84%
So if I'm growing mouse
cells, then what I do

00:44:59.247 --> 00:45:01.330 align:middle line:84%
is look at mouse blood,
see what it's made out of,

00:45:01.330 --> 00:45:04.280 align:middle line:84%
and then try to make a synthetic
version of that called culture

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:05.080 align:middle line:90%
medium.

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:06.210 align:middle line:90%
So here's the point--

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:08.310 align:middle line:84%
genetically identical
cells in three dishes

00:45:08.310 --> 00:45:10.170 align:middle line:84%
but slightly
different environment

00:45:10.170 --> 00:45:12.060 align:middle line:90%
because of the chemistry.

00:45:12.060 --> 00:45:14.120 align:middle line:84%
In one dish, the
cells form muscle.

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:16.200 align:middle line:84%
In a second dish,
the cells form bone.

00:45:16.200 --> 00:45:19.060 align:middle line:84%
And in a third dish, the
cells form fat cells.

00:45:19.060 --> 00:45:22.920 align:middle line:84%
Significance-- what controls
the fate of the cells?

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:26.550 align:middle line:84%
Point-- they were all
genetically identical.

00:45:26.550 --> 00:45:30.780 align:middle line:84%
The environment is what was
selecting the genetic activity

00:45:30.780 --> 00:45:32.920 align:middle line:90%
of the cells.

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:36.280 align:middle line:84%
>> People who have the
same DNA, who have the same

00:45:36.280 --> 00:45:40.570 align:middle line:84%
susceptibility to illness, one
can become ill and the other

00:45:40.570 --> 00:45:42.070 align:middle line:90%
can stay well.

00:45:42.070 --> 00:45:44.980 align:middle line:84%
One can heal, and
the other can't,

00:45:44.980 --> 00:45:50.200 align:middle line:84%
all because they optimize the
environmental factors that

00:45:50.200 --> 00:45:51.820 align:middle line:90%
control gene activity.

00:45:51.820 --> 00:45:54.550 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the field
of epigenetics is all about.

00:45:54.550 --> 00:45:57.940 align:middle line:90%


00:45:57.940 --> 00:45:59.620 align:middle line:84%
>> The nature of
biology is simple.

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:02.470 align:middle line:10%
Biological organisms
adapt their biology

00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:05.920 align:middle line:10%
to fit into an environment.

00:46:05.920 --> 00:46:09.130 align:middle line:84%
Let's say I'm looking at the
activity of my liver cells

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:11.860 align:middle line:84%
in the body, and I say,
well, my liver cells

00:46:11.860 --> 00:46:14.390 align:middle line:84%
should be adjusting to what's
going on in the environment.

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:16.570 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well, how does
a liver cell know what's

00:46:16.570 --> 00:46:17.390 align:middle line:90%
going on in the environment?

00:46:17.390 --> 00:46:18.580 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is this--

00:46:18.580 --> 00:46:21.610 align:middle line:84%
